06655nam a22009975i 9783110497151DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20162017gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831104971517 a10.1515/97831104971512doi  a(DE-B1597)469932  a(OCoLC)979847568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aDiscourse Particles :bFormal Approaches to their Syntax and Semantics /ced. by Josef Bayer, Volker Struckmeier. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (VI, 334 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLinguistische Arbeiten ,x0344-6727 ;v56400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe status quo of research on discourse particles in syntax and semantics -- tThe syntax and semantics of discourse particles -- tWhat you see is what you get: Chinese sentence-final particles as head-final complementizers -- tThe syntax of Swedish modal particles -- tDiscourse particles and hvað-exclamatives -- tRoot infinitivals and modal particles. An interim report -- tModal particles ≠ modal particles (= modal particles) -- tDiscourse particles “embedded”: German ja in adjectival phrases -- tCombining ja and doch: A case of discourse structural iconicity -- tDiscourse marker = discourse particle = thetical = modal particle? A futile comparison -- tStressed and unstressed particles in Old Indic -- tOn the status and the interpretation of the left-peripheral sentence particles inu and ia in Old High German -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aParticles have for the longest time been ignored by linguistic research. School-type grammars ignored them since they did not fit into pre-conceived notions of categories, and since they did not seem to enter into grammatical relations commonly discussed in the genre. Only in the last century did some publications discuss particles – and even then only from the perspective of their discourse and pragmatic functions, i.e. their dependance on certain previous contexts, and concluded that the function of particles for the grammar of sentences and their interpretation remains obscure. The current volume presents 11 new articles that take a fresh look at particles: As it turns out, particles inform many aspects of syntax and semantics, too – both diachronically and synchronically: Particles are shown to have fascinating syntactic properties with respect to projection, locality, movement and scope. Their interpretative contributions can be studied with the rigorous methods of formal semantics. Cross-linguistic and diachronic investigations shed new light on the genesis and development of these intriguing – and under-estimated – kinds of lexical elements.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aFormale Semantik. 4aFormale Syntax. 4aSprachgeschichte. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aFormal Semantics.  aLanguage History.  aSyntax.1 aAbraham, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayer, Josef, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBayer, Josef, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEgg, Markus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutzmann, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGärtner, Hans-Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJunnan Pan, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJónsson, Jóhannes Gísli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLühr, Rosemarie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMursell, Johannes,